tspan.tspan: Figure Y: host genotype differentiation of skin microbiome.
A) Change of alpha diversity (Faith's Phylogenetic Diversity) over generations.
Diversity of six individual (i) embryo recipient mother (RM) mice of mixed genotype B6CF1 (gray), housed in three cages (c) is given as the
red box and circles. Following line plots summarize the diversity of six offspring generations (P to F5), which were inbreed in three fully
separated cage lineages (l) per genotype (C57BL6/J in blue and BALB/c in orange). Diversity of six control mice per genotype and per
independent environments (Duesseldorf and Janvier) is visualized as four boxes and circles on the right hand side. Top x axis labels indicate
number of individual mice (i), number of cages (c) in which mice were housed and number of cage lineages (l). B) Beta diversity distance
(measured as weighted UniFrac) to RM samples. Line plot summarizes distance of C57BLK6/J and BALB/C samples to RM samples, in blue
and orange, respectively. Green line plot indicates distance between both genotypes. For reference, the gray dashed line is the mean
pairwise distance between individuals housed in the same cage, i.e. lower resolution limit as these mice should be biological replicates.
Brown dotted line is the mean distance of individuals from two different cages (963 individual pairs: i-i) of the same genotype, cage lineage
and generation. C) Beta diversity distance (measured as weighted UniFrac) to control samples as a proxy of environment. Solid lines stand
for control mice from Duesseldorf (Germany), dashed lines from Janvier (France). D) Cage lineage (X axis) difference might be explained by
mouse behavior, e.g. level of stress induced by different numbers of cage mates. E) Inter individual distances of cages with few (=1-3 mice,
green) and many (=4-5 mice, purple) mice per cage. We used Mann-Whitney for all statistical tests with Benjamini-Hochberg correction for
multiple testing (ns: not significant, ****: p 0.0001, ***: p 0.001, **: p 0.01, * p 0.05)
